{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8c1a2431-1d6f-4072-8499-ce838953f86b","content":"This repository doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump` (that's a CoreCLR tool). On macOS, use the OS-level mechanisms instead:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app so the kernel writes a core file on crash.\n\n2. **Check for macOS crash reports** — macOS automatically saves crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files named after your process.\n\n3. **Use `lldb` to inspect the core** — if a core file was written (typically to `/cores/core.<pid>`):\n   ```\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n4. **Ensure `/cores` is writable** — on modern macOS with SIP, `/cores` may not be writable. You may need to `sudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores`.\n\n5. **Check `kern.corefile` sysctl** — verify the core file path pattern:\n   ```\n   sysctl kern.corefile\n   ```\n\n6. **For symbolicated analysis**, build with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`) so `lldb` can show meaningful backtraces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3cbc3bf9-ad68-4968-b4e9-d939cb94c221","outputTokens":350,"requestId":"AC04:18E49A:14024DA:1676642:6A0671B1"},"id":"74c859ca-7fe2-4ca2-97b2-f880644ebca5","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:07:06.350Z","parentId":"08ff2182-68ab-4b18-8116-6378022b3f54"}
